<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?><rss xmlns:dc="http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/" xmlns:content="http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/" xmlns:atom="http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom" version="2.0"><channel><title><![CDATA[Peter Hoggarth]]></title><description><![CDATA[Full stack software developer.]]></description><link>https://peterhoggarth.com</link><generator>RSS for Node</generator><lastBuildDate>Fri, 26 Apr 2019 21:20:57 GMT</lastBuildDate><item><title><![CDATA[Deploying a Gatsby site to Github Pages]]></title><description><![CDATA[Gatsby makes it very easy to deploy a site to github pages.  The first step will be installing the github pages package We will then need to…]]></description><link>https://peterhoggarth.com/deploying-gatsby--github-pages/</link><guid isPermaLink="false">https://peterhoggarth.com/deploying-gatsby--github-pages/</guid><pubDate>Mon, 08 Apr 2019 18:15:00 GMT</pubDate><content:encoded>&lt;p&gt;Gatsby makes it very easy to deploy a site to github pages. &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The first step will be installing the github pages package&lt;br&gt;
&lt;code class=&quot;language-text&quot;&gt;$npm i --save-dev gh-pages&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;We will then need to add a deployment script to package.json&lt;br&gt;
&lt;code class=&quot;language-text&quot;&gt;&amp;quot;deploy&amp;quot;: &amp;quot;gatsby build --prefix-paths &amp;amp;&amp;amp; gh-pages -d public -b gh-pages&amp;quot;&lt;/code&gt;&lt;br&gt;
Make sure to specify the branch you’d like github to use in the -b paramater.&lt;br&gt;
I would recomend keeping your source code, and github pages brances seperate, as you won’t want the build files in your main development branch&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Github will server our site with the following URL structure:
&lt;code class=&quot;language-text&quot;&gt;username.github.io/repo&lt;/code&gt;&lt;br&gt;
We will need to specify the repository name in order to serve our site properly. This is handled by the &lt;code class=&quot;language-text&quot;&gt;--prefix-paths&lt;/code&gt; flag, but we will need to provide gatsby with the name of our repo.&lt;br&gt;
This can be handled in the gatsby-config.js file, by adding &lt;code class=&quot;language-text&quot;&gt;pathPrefix: &amp;quot;/gatsby-blog&amp;quot;,&lt;/code&gt; to the exports.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Now, all that’s left is running &lt;code class=&quot;language-text&quot;&gt;$npm run deploy&lt;/code&gt;, and the site will be up and running!&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The full instructions can be found in the &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.gatsbyjs.org/docs/how-gatsby-works-with-github-pages/&quot;&gt;gatsby documentation&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</content:encoded></item><item><title><![CDATA[Hello World]]></title><description><![CDATA[Hello, world!
